Maintainer: Gabriel Guillou guillou.gabriel@gmail.com
Homepage: https://github.com/DaemonCores/DaemonCores-VE
Section: admin
Priority: optional
Depends: ipmitool, kmod, openipmi, gawk, {{ DEPS }}
Description: generic self-calibrating temperature-driven fan controller
 A lightweight bash daemon that regulates fan speed from temperature. Backends,
 auto-detected: a profiled IPMI BMC (servers), a ChromeOS/Framework Embedded
 Controller via ectool (laptops with no IPMI/PWM), or a writable hwmon PWM.
 .
 Every temperature sensor is classified into its component profile with two
 sourced values: an optimal target the curve tracks in real time, and a hard
 critical. Cool-preferring parts (CPU, GPU, VRM, RAM, battery) are held cool;
 warm-preferring parts (SSD, HDD) are left warm. The component furthest above its
 own target drives the auto-calibrated curve, so every part sits at its optimum.
 A sensor whose name is unknown but whose critical is high (generic server
 sensors) is still regulated, preserving the historical behaviour.
 .
 The critical is a bare hard-safety threshold (reading >= crit forces 100%, no
 margin) that should never fire in normal use. Implausible readings/thresholds
 (phantom or unpopulated sensors) are rejected. Writing the fan speed uses an
 auto-detected vendor profile over IPMI (Dell iDRAC verified), ectool on an EC,
 or hwmon PWM; an unknown IPMI vendor stays in read-only monitor mode. Regulation
 is handed back to automatic control on stop or on loss of communication.
